<main>
  <section>
    <article>
      <img src="https://i.imgur.com/UZAS7wf.jpg" alt="Portrait of Leonardo da Vinci" class="image-left">
      <h2>Early Life</h2>
      <p>
        Leonardo di ser Piero da Vinci, commonly known as Leonardo da Vinci, was born on April 15, 1452, in Vinci, Italy. 
        He was born out of wedlock to Caterina, a peasant woman, and Ser Piero, a notary. 
        Leonardo's early life was spent in Vinci, and he was raised by his father and stepmothers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Despite his lack of formal education, Leonardo showed an early talent for drawing and artistic expression. 
        He quickly gained recognition in his hometown for his artistic abilities and inquisitive mind.
      </p>
      <p>
        At the age of 14, Leonardo began an apprenticeship with Andrea del Verrocchio, a renowned artist in Florence. 
        Under Verrocchio's guidance, Leonardo honed his skills in painting, sculpture, and engineering.
      </p>
      <p>
        Leonardo's curiosity and thirst for knowledge led him to study various subjects, including mathematics, anatomy, and engineering, during his formative years.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article>
      <img src="https://i.imgur.com/dntZrNd.jpg" alt="Mona Lisa" class="image-right">
      <h2>Contributions and Achievements</h2>
      <p>
        Leonardo da Vinci is widely recognized as one of the most diversely talented individuals ever to have lived. 
        He excelled in various fields including painting, sculpture, architecture, science, mathematics, engineering, anatomy, and literature.
        Some of his most famous works include the Mona Lisa, The Last Supper, and Vitruvian Man.
      </p>
      <p>
        Apart from his artistic masterpieces, Leonardo made significant contributions to scientific and engineering principles. 
        He conducted studies on anatomy, dissecting human cadavers to understand the structure and function of the human body. 
        His notebooks, containing meticulously detailed sketches and observations, are considered some of the most valuable documents in history.
      </p>
      <p>
        Leonardo's curiosity and innovation extended to various inventions and designs, including flying machines, military weapons, and hydraulic systems. 
        Although many of his designs were not realized during his lifetime, they demonstrated his forward-thinking and pioneering spirit.
      </p>
      <div class="clear"></div>
    </article>
  </section>
